00:01.140 --> 00:12.660
OK, the tape is rolling. OK, first of all, could you tell me if you, as a
youngster, did you come from the fan structure in science fiction? No, my

00:12.660 --> 00:30.460
experience with science fiction was very solitary for most of my period of
growing up. I discovered the area of the fantastic. I think I can trace back to

00:30.460 --> 00:45.240
when I was eight or nine years old when I found some old Edgar Rice Burroughs
novels in my grandmother's back closet and one by one read them and became

00:45.240 --> 01:02.400
entranced by it. That was followed by a, period during the thirties, when the
pulp adventure magazines were at their height. And my father and his brothers,

01:02.640 --> 01:16.900
my uncles, would buy these 10-cent magazines and bring them home and I would
read them. Mostly they seemed to prefer the pulp

01:16.900 --> 01:28.500
hero magazines like Doc Savage and operator number five and the spider and the
shadow and magazines of this kind of which I, you know, G8 is battle laces. But

01:28.500 --> 01:39.680
eventually I discovered a secondhand magazine store in Kansas City where I was
born and grew up. And when I finished reading the magazines, I'd take them down

01:39.680 --> 01:52.440
to this magazine store and trade them for science fiction magazines, which I
then devoured. so I grew up not really knowing any other science fiction readers

01:52.440 --> 02:04.200
my brother, older brother, read a little but not with the enthusiasm that I did
so my first contact with other readers, much less

02:07.320 --> 02:19.820
other writers was after I'd been writing for four years I was aware that there
was this fan structure because in some of the magazines like Startling Stories

02:19.820 --> 02:31.220
and Thrilling Wonder Stories and even in Astounding, there would be letter
columns with the names of people. Gradually, I began to recognize a few of them

02:31.220 --> 02:47.760
and I realized that there were other readers, but it wasn't until I attended the
World Science Fiction Convention of 1952 which was held in Chicago and I was

02:47.760 --> 02:59.400
urged to go by the company I worked for at that time a paperback publishing
house for whom I was supposed to be their science fiction expert and they

02:59.400 --> 03:11.900
suggested they pay my way if I went to the 60-80 miles down from Racine,
Wisconsin to Chicago and attend the convention to make contacts and that was my

03:11.900 --> 03:27.460
first experience with really meeting other readers and other writers and agents
and editors and the whole paraphernalia of the science fiction world. Okay,

03:27.660 --> 03:38.820
good. Can you recall the circumstances? I believe it was in 1949, of your first
published story. Yes, I had

03:38.820 --> 03:54.240
read science fiction, as I said, from oh about the age of 8 or 9, and read it
seriously for a while during the middle 30s. And at the age of oh about 15 or 16

03:54.240 --> 04:07.480
I had written some science fiction stories, though with no particular skill, and
I usually, like most beginning writers, didn't even finish most of them. I can

04:07.480 --> 04:08.880
only remember one that I finished.

04:11.600 --> 04:24.020
But then the college came along, and the war came along, and I got involved in
both of them, and it wasn't until after I'd come back from service and gotten my

04:24.020 --> 04:39.120
bachelor's degree and had actually had about a year of graduate study, that I
decided to try full-time writing. I had been interested in theater, playwriting,

04:39.760 --> 04:52.760
but I decided I didn't want to get a degree in that in the speech and theater
area, but I was fascinated by the notion of radio writing. So I returned from

04:52.760 --> 05:05.860
Northwestern University to Kansas City with the notion of writing a series of
half-hour radio dramas based on Kansas City history and getting some local radio

05:05.860 --> 05:15.860
station to produce them. And I actually wrote four of these and did the research
for them and so forth, and then went around to the radio stations and found out

05:15.860 --> 05:28.540
that not any of them were interested. so i had a wife to sport and i sat down
and wrote the kind of thing that i've been reading all this time first time

05:28.540 --> 05:41.160
seriously and wrote a story called paradox which i sent off to astounding and
astounding set it back then i sent it off to amazing and amazing set it back And

05:41.160 --> 05:53.440
I sent it off to Thrilling Wonder Stories, which was the third magazine that had
been unstarved in stories that were published by the same chain. And one day I

05:53.440 --> 06:03.180
got a letter back saying, I like your story, Paradox, and I'll pay you $80 for
it. So I thought, marvelous. I'd really stumbled onto something that was

06:03.180 --> 06:13.960
tremendous. And so I meanwhile had been writing another story, which was a story
called Communication, and I created it the same way I sent it off to Astounding

06:13.960 --> 06:26.800
first and I think maybe I sent it off second after I got rejected by Astounding
to Throwing Wonder Stories and the same editor Sam Merwin Jr. bought it and that

06:26.800 --> 06:40.680
was the story which happened to be published first in Startling Stories in
September of 1949 where the first story I actually wrote which is Paradox, was

06:40.680 --> 06:45.620
published the following month in Thrilling Wonder Stories in October.

06:47.680 --> 06:56.960
You didn't have to go through a long process of getting rejection slips then,
did you? No, as a matter of fact, sometimes when I talk to aspiring young

06:56.960 --> 07:10.460
writers, and they turn to me and they say, how many rejection slips did you get
before you finally sold a story? And I look a little sheepish, because I know

07:10.460 --> 07:21.520
it's not the answer they want. And I said, I sold the first story I ever really
wrote seriously. And their faces fall. And then I follow it up immediately by

07:21.520 --> 07:35.420
saying, but of course Ray Bradbury had 75 to 100 stories rejected before he sold
one. And look what he got to. Yeah, okay. This next question, I'm not quite sure

07:35.420 --> 07:40.580
how to phrase it, But I've always been fascinated by the

07:40.580 --> 07:49.760
split in your relationship to science fiction. You know, it seems to me that you
must have at one time made a decision to be an academic and to be a writer at

07:49.760 --> 08:00.120
the same time. I wonder if that was a hard decision or if you ever considered
full-time writing. I did, as a matter of fact, write full-time for a period of a

08:00.120 --> 08:18.520
little more than three years, It was a year in 1948, 49, and I went back to
school then and got a master's degree, but I continued to write. And then after

08:18.520 --> 08:28.460
I'd worked for this paperback publisher, after I got my master's degree, worked
for a paperback publisher for a year and a half, I found out that I'd sold four

08:28.460 --> 08:44.660
stories that I hadn't known about and decided to go back to full-time writing.
So I did write full-time from the fall of 1942 until the late summer of 1955.

08:45.460 --> 09:01.280
And really much of the groundwork for the later books that I published and the
success that I had, I think, such as it was based upon that freelance period. I

09:01.280 --> 09:15.540
didn't make a lot of money at it, below the poverty level, but my needs were
fairly simple at that time and what it later paid off in the sense that the

09:15.540 --> 09:24.200
stories that I wrote appeared in books and some of them even were made in the
movies and all that sort of thing. And if I'd had the money for them at the time

09:24.200 --> 09:37.440
I was writing them, I would have thought I was very well off indeed. But it was
after 1955, or in the fall of 1955, after my wife and I had moved back to

09:37.440 --> 09:48.260
Lawrence, Kansas, simply as a place to live, but I got involved, almost by
accident, with teaching at the university from which I'd gotten my two degrees

09:48.260 --> 09:59.760
at the University of Kansas, and became involved with other aspects of the
university, edited the alumni magazine for three years, and then became director

09:59.760 --> 10:14.940
of public relations for the university for 12 years before returning to full
-time teaching and writing in 1970. But looking back upon it, I know, I think

10:14.940 --> 10:29.900
right from the beginning, I had the feeling that I wanted to do criticism in the
area. My first 10 stories, for instance, were published under a pseudonym of

10:29.900 --> 10:44.700
Edwin James. I began to use my own name with the 11th story. But the reason that
I can remember now for doing that was the fact that I thought I would write

10:44.700 --> 10:56.660
criticism about science fiction and I wanted to save my real name for that. But
after 10 stories, I decided that was foolish. and I ought to use my real name

10:56.660 --> 11:11.400
for everything. But looking back upon it, I think the academic interest was
there right from the beginning. Okay, that's interesting. I want to ask you,

11:11.500 --> 11:20.800
obviously, a couple questions, at least on your criticism. But first, could you
give me sort of a brief overview of the things that you do at the University of

11:20.800 --> 11:27.460
Kansas that involve science fiction? I imagine it's probably one of the most
active university science fiction programs in the country, if not the most

11:27.460 --> 11:38.800
active. We have a lot of things going on. I've been fortunate to have found a
colleague here, Stephen Goldman, who is interested in science fiction, although

11:38.800 --> 11:53.760
his basic academic discipline is the medieval, period. it's a strange
phenomenon. I think that a great many science fiction academicians

11:55.320 --> 12:09.000
have their expertise as medievalists. I don't know what the connection is, but I
suspect that there is one. But we also, because of our interest here, I think

12:09.000 --> 12:19.100
have attracted some graduate students who are interested in the area, some of
whom have gotten degrees not in science fiction because we don't offer one, but

12:19.100 --> 12:34.800
in science fiction-related areas. I have one graduate student now who's doing
his dissertation on my work and another one who graduated last year who did a

12:34.800 --> 12:51.260
creative dissertation of a book of science fiction stories. So we have had that
body of graduate students who have taught science fiction classes at the

12:51.260 --> 13:06.060
sophomore level as one of the required courses in composition and literature.
And I also traditionally teach a science fiction course, an undergraduate and

13:06.060 --> 13:16.520
graduate science fiction course each year, although my primary duties in the
English department are the teaching of fiction writing. Perhaps our most

13:16.520 --> 13:29.640
interesting science fiction offering, however, is the three-week Intensive
English Institute on the teaching of science fiction that we offer in the

13:29.640 --> 13:44.580
summer. we realized a number of years ago that there were a lot of people faced
with the task sometimes self-assumed sometimes assigned of teaching a science

13:44.580 --> 13:57.640
fiction course and they were largely unprepared because there had been no
academic program on science fiction certainly not on the teaching of science

13:57.640 --> 14:19.500
fiction So we set up this intensive three-week workshop to offer teachers the
opportunity to attend and get a six-credit-hour program in science fiction, all

14:19.500 --> 14:29.940
aspects of science fiction, in just three weeks. It's a very intensive
experience. We bring in several science fiction writers besides myself. This

14:29.940 --> 14:45.960
year we're having Gordon Dixon and Theodore Sturgeon and Frederick Poole, and it
has been a most successful and satisfying experience. This summer the Institute

14:45.960 --> 14:50.260
will be held from July 5th to July 23rd.

14:53.820 --> 15:05.800
okay, by the way I am a medievalist myself too that is kind of strange but my
field is medieval literature too is that right? why do you think medievalists

15:05.800 --> 15:15.840
are attracted to it? I don't know, I never thought of it until you just
mentioned it I know half a dozen people Tom Shippey who is an English

15:15.840 --> 15:30.900
medievalist who teaches now at Leeds University I know the editor of Pocketbook
Science Fiction, David Hartwell, is a medievalist with a Ph.D. in medieval

15:30.900 --> 15:46.680
literature, and I think there must be a number of others. And I think my own
feeling is that medieval literature perhaps requires the same kind of world

15:46.680 --> 16:00.220
construction. of imagination, and, you know, building up an entirely new world
out of different concepts, much like science fiction. At least that's the theory

16:00.220 --> 16:09.880
that I'm proposing. Well, that's interesting. Yeah, okay, I never thought of it.
Okay, listen, we teach a class here at Odessa College, and we use the Road to

16:09.880 --> 16:18.720
Science Fiction series, which I consider to be a very valuable and unique
endeavor. Thank you. It's something we needed. I'd like to ask you just a couple

16:18.720 --> 16:30.060
questions on that. First of all, for that particular approach to science
fiction, was there any kind of impetus or idea that caused you to start that

16:30.060 --> 16:43.000
series? Maybe it'd be best to give you a kind of history of its development. I
had, when I first went back to full-time teaching, had been asked if I would

16:43.000 --> 16:55.480
teach a science fiction course, which is different from the experience at most
universities where there is some resistance to the notion of doing that. And I

16:55.480 --> 17:09.640
accepted because I had the feeling that there wasn't a good history of science
fiction and that this course would give me the incentive to write it. So I sat

17:09.640 --> 17:23.580
down and wrote very fast and ended up with 13 chapters representing about 13
lectures for the 14-week semester.

17:25.000 --> 17:42.000
And these chapters, or these lectures, became the 13 chapters in a book of mine,
which appeared in about, I guess it was 75, after some delays, as alternate

17:42.000 --> 17:52.800
world the Illustrated History of Science Fiction. And it did reasonably well.
There were some problems with its publication and so forth, including the

17:52.800 --> 18:06.980
delays. But it is still remembered today in spite of being out of print as being
one of the best histories of science fiction, complementing Brian Aldis' Billion

18:06.980 --> 18:16.480
-Year Spree, which he was doing at the same time, but his book came out a couple
years earlier but as one consequence of its publication I got a call one day

18:16.480 --> 18:31.280
from an editor at New American Library who was admiring it and asked me if I'd
like to do a book for them My initial reaction was that I felt that we needed a

18:31.280 --> 18:45.920
good collection of essays about science fiction and I proposed a book of these
rather fortunately I think for me it was turned down at New American Library and

18:45.920 --> 19:05.880
they said they'd rather have some stories and I knew also that that I really
felt the need for anthologies which covered more than the brief span of the 20s

19:05.880 --> 19:19.920
to the 60s which most anthologies did, and there really wasn't much in the 20s
or 30s, most of it covered the period of the 40s and 50s. So I said yes, and I

19:19.920 --> 19:34.460
sent them a proposal for the first volume of the Road Science Fiction. At that
time, all we knew that there would be would be one volume, which covered the

19:34.460 --> 19:53.060
period from the earliest prehistory of literature, not to mention science
fiction, up to 1900, and the H.G. Wells' early stories and novels. By the time I

19:53.060 --> 20:01.800
got finished with the manuscript, I had felt that it really, unlike most books,
came out even better than I thought it was going to, and I propose that we go

20:01.800 --> 20:17.380
ahead with a second and third volume. They said, let's wait and see how this
does, and eventually, after it had done better than they thought, they agreed

20:17.380 --> 20:35.740
that I could go on to volume 2 and 3, which covered the period from 1900 to
approximately 1940, and then from 1940 to 1970 or 70, actually the latest one,

20:35.840 --> 20:48.420
76 I think. And I did those together, but by the time I got to the third volume,
I realized that I wasn't going to be able to get in everything that I wanted and

20:48.420 --> 20:59.820
suggested we go ahead and do a fourth volume. But they said, well, let's wait
and see how these do. As a consequence, however, of the fact that these did very

20:59.820 --> 21:10.980
well, or well accepted. They finally agreed that I could go ahead and do a
fourth volume, and I've just completed that, sent in the manuscript, and the

21:10.980 --> 21:25.000
fourth volume Road to Science Fiction is scheduled to appear in October of this
year, and it will cover the period overlapping a little bit with Volume 3, the

21:25.000 --> 21:29.900
period from 1950 to 1981.

21:32.260 --> 21:37.380
The last volume is going to be a little different from the first three, however.

21:40.080 --> 21:57.040
The first three are on a historical basis, as I've indicated, and you have
noted, with much of the emphasis being on the development of science fiction and

21:57.040 --> 22:10.720
the stories generally selected or the ones which were important in the
development of science fiction or typical of a certain period or a certain

22:10.720 --> 22:23.260
style. In the more current story, this is much more difficult to determine. You
can't really say what stories are important until much after they've been

22:23.260 --> 22:34.820
published, and you can't certainly say which are typical until you decide what
the period really stands for. So what I did in the fourth volume was to select

22:34.820 --> 22:49.600
stories that I thought dealt with the literary uses of science fiction. and so
that the volume is primarily concerned not with questions of generic importance

22:49.600 --> 22:52.360
but the question of literary uses

22:54.920 --> 22:59.700
okay that was a very complete answer in fact you probably got a couple of my
next questions with that one

23:02.700 --> 23:12.720
let's see could you just say in volume one could you briefly comment on I think
the idea or the concept behind that particular volume was that before science

23:12.720 --> 23:20.640
fiction could exist, that man had to discover that there was a future and there
was such a thing as progress. Could you briefly explain that? Yes, it seems to

23:20.640 --> 23:34.000
me that the essential nature of science fiction is that it deals with change. In
fact, in order for us to recognize a story or a novel as being science fiction,

23:34.000 --> 23:49.240
we have to identify that part of it which is different from here and now. our
everyday world. And so it deals with how people would react in changed

23:49.240 --> 23:50.380
circumstances.

23:52.500 --> 24:07.660
So, up to approximately the time of the Industrial Revolution, the very concept
of change itself was alien to human minds. For most of humanity's history, it

24:07.660 --> 24:19.700
seems to me, and of course as a medievalist, Maybe I'm venturing into your area.
But it

24:19.700 --> 24:37.840
seems to me, looking back over the history of humanity, that mostly people saw
change as being only the eternal circle of the seasons changing from spring to

24:37.840 --> 24:53.620
summer to fall to winter and back again, or if there was change in people's
circumstances, it was usually change for the worst. That is, the king would die

24:53.620 --> 25:09.020
and the empire would be thrown into turmoil or there would be war lost or run or
barbarians would come in pillaging and burning and killing and other kinds of

25:09.020 --> 25:21.600
terrible things, or there would be droughts or plagues or all sorts of bad
things. But so as a consequence throughout most of man's history that if there

25:21.600 --> 25:38.140
have been legends and myths of a golden age which man once existed in and from
which humanity has been expelled or has degenerated or deteriorated. And it

25:38.140 --> 25:52.200
wasn't until the investor revolution and, of course, the scientific perceptions
that preceded it and accompanied it, and which began to create change that

25:52.200 --> 26:07.160
people saw could be beneficial. over which they might be able to exercise some
control. That is, it was man-made change created by human desires and

26:07.160 --> 26:21.980
intelligence, and it could be controlled by humanity's exercise of intelligence.
And it seems to me that science fiction was the literary response to that

26:21.980 --> 26:22.560
recognition.

