29:12.080 --> 29:15.520
you know, all of it's done 50% better than the average book.

29:18.540 --> 29:27.920
This is sort of a general question. Feel free to answer it as briefly as you'd
like. Why do you think there's a need? I think you do think there is, a need for

29:27.920 --> 29:29.860
science fiction, criticism, and scholarship.

29:33.360 --> 29:48.720
I think that a category of fiction like science fiction, I hate to continue to
use the word genre because it's not really traditionally a genre. It is a set of

29:48.720 --> 30:04.520
conventions and a set of expectations. But in this particular area, which has
largely been ignored by the apparatus of criticism in this country and in other

30:04.520 --> 30:17.560
parts of the world as well, because it's not been considered important enough to
merit criticism. It's considered to be a pulp literature, a popular literature,

30:17.980 --> 30:34.660
and in a sense beneath criticism. And as a consequence, it has developed largely
under its own impetus without any kinds of efforts of critical minds to look at

30:34.660 --> 30:52.140
it and try to appraise it, say, what's good and what's bad according to some
kind of standards that can be established, and as well to teach, to help the

30:52.140 --> 31:10.020
other critical areas of English literature to appraise it differently, to
understand that unlike other kinds of literature, science fiction has special

31:10.020 --> 31:25.760
things that it does and has special ways that it does it, and to appraise
science fiction by the same kinds of standards that you apply to traditional

31:25.760 --> 31:39.760
literature, science fiction is always going to come up short. It doesn't do the
same things. It deals not with characters, but with change. And so it seems to

31:39.760 --> 31:55.940
me that there needs to be two different routes, or there are two desirable ends
for criticism. One is to educate the non-science fiction part of the literary

31:55.940 --> 32:09.480
world to the special requirements of science fiction and its special
accomplishments. The other is to exercise and apply a set of standards to

32:09.480 --> 32:24.540
science fiction itself to improve the breed, so to speak. Okay, fine. I only
have two more questions on this particular line that I've been following. Your

32:24.540 --> 32:32.980
book, Alternate Worlds, I didn't have a real specific question on that. I've
used it as a research aid, and found it very useful. Of course, I read Brian

32:32.980 --> 32:41.600
Aldis's and Donald Walheim's and so forth, histories of science fiction. Do you
think there's room for any more histories of science fiction? Well, they're

32:41.600 --> 32:54.680
still coming out. And, you know, whether there are any more needed, I suspect
that as these books get dated, new appraisals are necessary. And indeed, if a

32:54.680 --> 33:11.400
new kind of perception of science fiction emerges, there certainly needs to be a
reappraisal of the history that is to either support it or refute it. I don't

33:11.400 --> 33:24.480
know that we really need more history. I suspect that maybe in another 10 or 15
years, maybe a new history will be more needed.

33:27.260 --> 33:37.100
Fine, okay, my other question this is one we ask all of the authors that we talk
to and it's sort of a touchy subject with them it has to do with the relation

33:37.100 --> 33:45.800
between science fiction and mainstream I read some of your ideas on it and I
can't quite make up my mind I think in one essay I think it was the one that

33:45.800 --> 33:55.380
appeared in Bretner's book you said that science fiction and the mainstream were
becoming closer but that you thought that perhaps it would be a good idea for

33:55.380 --> 34:04.360
science fiction to keep its unique qualities. Whereas in another piece, I think
it was the introduction to Breaking Point, you said or implied that it was a

34:04.360 --> 34:16.220
good idea that they do come back together where they belong and that they should
blend. I wondered if you could specify your feelings about that. Well, I guess

34:16.220 --> 34:20.300
maybe I do have mixed

34:20.300 --> 34:22.080
notions about it.

34:24.880 --> 34:36.140
I think that existing separately, science fiction, has attained certain kinds of
strengths

34:36.140 --> 34:56.100
created by isolation, but also certain kinds of weaknesses. But I also think
that the mainstream of literature has certain qualities and selection processes

34:56.100 --> 35:13.560
that could benefit science fiction. I guess the ideal, and I think in a certain
sense it is happening, the ideal would be that good books ought to be published

35:16.500 --> 35:31.340
essentially without generic identification. And they are being so published. I
